3825,0.16736989,-0.04399388,0.10917671,-0.01730878,-0.01696007,0.01725288,0.01349799,0.05421157,0.03453863,-0.03188090,0.03791326,-0.06877904,0.03485291,-0.01431653,0.06856278,0.01214007,0.00260118,-0.00987448,-0.01506787,-0.01260927,0.01831491,-0.01176523,0.03537172,0.01287058,-0.07564761,-0.04589138,0.06109395,0.01739132,-0.04236534,-0.03373355,0.01214140,-0.02945829,0.02888918,-0.01085347,-0.01261964,-0.01051504,-0.00989468,0.07408521,0.06804769,-0.01982466,0.06122084,0.03980206,0.03637914]',E'Overview\n\nIn gRPC, a client application can directly call a method on a server application\non a different machine as if it were a local object, making it easier for you to\ncreate distributed applications and services. As in many RPC systems, gRPC is\nbased around the idea of defining a service, specifying the methods that can be\ncalled remotely with their parameters and return types. On the server side, the\nserver implements this interface and runs a gRPC server to handle client calls.','{"source": "grpc", "version": "1.65", "language": "proto", "title": "Introduction", "section_title": "introduction", "url": "https://github.com/grpc/grpc.io/blob/main/content/en/docs/what-is-grpc/introduction.md", "topics": "grpc,rpc,introduction", "categories": "rpc,networking,proto"}');
