6,-0.02896698,0.04136695,0.00882251,-0.01125100,-0.01007708,0.04018553,0.02390875,-0.01321796,0.02182459,0.01001803,-0.04947994,0.02198735,-0.02749416,-0.00480966,0.05444069,0.01158261,-0.03034730,-0.01637809,-0.01656163,0.04224805,-0.02548105,0.04184214,0.02317231,-0.09910439,-0.05193071,0.00169987,-0.03054041,-0.02887767,-0.05498585,-0.00142733,-0.03284609,-0.04871235,0.02493668,0.00229792,-0.02134238,0.00303846,0.04568862,0.04775815,-0.00406485,0.12109115,0.05378496,-0.00009060]',E'RPC termination\n\nIn gRPC, both the client and server make independent and local determinations of\nthe success of the call, and their conclusions may not match. This means that,\nfor example, you could have an RPC that finishes successfully on the server side\n("I have sent all my responses!") but fails on the client side ("The responses\narrived after my deadline!"). It''s also possible for a server to decide to\ncomplete before a client has sent all its requests.','{"source": "grpc", "version": "1.65", "language": "proto", "title": "Core Concepts", "section_title": "core-concepts", "url": "https://github.com/grpc/grpc.io/blob/main/content/en/docs/what-is-grpc/core-concepts.md", "topics": "grpc,rpc,core,concepts", "categories": "rpc,networking,proto"}');
