.13169302,-0.07964166,0.06019487,0.05748824,0.00590290,0.06268901,0.10636760,0.02539487,0.00969673,0.00015618,0.06690279,-0.00732877,-0.04696282,-0.07696017,-0.01580497,0.03320707,0.01333692,-0.01026853,-0.01409065,-0.05463207,0.03760448,-0.02265218,0.04627778,0.03425145,-0.04837522,-0.11620183,-0.03920683,-0.04074465,-0.06838768,-0.07514504,0.00123591,0.00447834,-0.01816341,0.08215985,0.03772666,-0.00952661,0.00371920,0.01771546,0.07184045,-0.04501630,0.04981351,0.02928687,-0.01321568]',E'Overview\n\nA deadline is used to specify a point in time past which a client is unwilling\nto wait for a response from a server. This simple idea is very important in\nbuilding robust distributed systems. Clients that do not wait around\nunnecessarily and servers that know when to give up processing requests will\nimprove the resource utilization and latency of your system.\n\nNote that while some language APIs have the concept of a __deadline__, others\nuse the idea of a __timeout__. When an API asks for a deadline, you provide a\npoint in time which the call should not go past. A timeout is the max duration\nof time that the call can take. A timeout can be converted to a deadline by\nadding the timeout to the current time when the application starts a call. For\nsimplicity, we will only refer to deadline in this document.','{"source": "grpc", "version": "1.65", "language": "proto", "title": "Deadlines", "section_title": "deadlines", "url": "https://github.com/grpc/grpc.io/blob/main/content/en/docs/guides/deadlines.md", "topics": "grpc,rpc,deadlines", "categories": "rpc,networking,proto"}');
