500,0.03055893,0.01620761,-0.00548862,0.01366619,0.03034695,0.00363708,0.02024900,-0.03584203,0.01688707,0.02961764,-0.02369555,0.02772123,-0.08061416,0.00044369,0.03888893,0.03666959,-0.00785165,0.02969502,0.02503997,0.04231213,-0.01793018,0.01899701,-0.02766317,-0.02881349,0.00236705,0.01357639,-0.01898931,-0.04439807,-0.07357902,0.02816803,-0.01837729,-0.05119619,0.01667708,-0.05157697,-0.05274992,0.00609378,0.01124900,0.07234585,-0.01932520,0.05384563,-0.02806194,0.01601685]',E'How configuring keepalive affects a call\n\nKeepalive is less likely to be triggered for unary RPCs with quick replies. Keepalive is primarily triggered when there is a long-lived RPC, which will fail if the keepalive check fails and the connection is closed.\n\nFor streaming RPCs, if the connection is closed, any in-progress RPCs will fail. If a call is streaming data, the stream will also be closed and any data that has not yet been sent will be lost.\n\n{{% alert title="Warning" color="warning" %}}\n  To avoid DDoSing, it''s important to take caution when setting the keepalive configurations. Thus, it is recommended to avoid enabling keepalive without calls and for clients to avoid configuring their keepalive much below one minute.\n{{% /alert %}}','{"source": "grpc", "version": "1.65", "language": "proto", "title": "Keepalive", "section_title": "keepalive", "url": "https://github.com/grpc/grpc.io/blob/main/content/en/docs/guides/keepalive.md", "topics": "grpc,rpc,keepalive", "categories": "rpc,networking,proto"}');
